41
00:02:40,019 --> 00:02:44,890
And even if it did exist, trumpets probably
didn’t bring it down.

42
00:02:44,890 --> 00:02:49,670
Looking at things etiologically, as we sometimes
do, is fun, but it isn’t ALWAYS possible

43
00:02:49,670 --> 00:02:52,790
to reconcile myths and historical remains.

44
00:02:52,790 --> 00:02:57,709
This is especially true of living cities,
which have to go about their business while

45
00:02:57,709 --> 00:03:00,780
also existing as a repository of stories about
them.

46
00:03:00,780 --> 00:03:05,299
Let’s start with a holy site mentioned in
the Bible, but still standing today, a holy

47
00:03:05,299 --> 00:03:09,360
site common to all three Abrahamic religions:
Jerusalem.

48
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:14,180
It might be an understatement to say that
Jerusalem has been the subject of many stories.

49
00:03:14,180 --> 00:03:18,999
And the imagery used to describe Jerusalem
changes dramatically depending upon who’s

50
00:03:18,999 --> 00:03:21,609
doing the describing and when.

51
00:03:21,609 --> 00:03:23,910
Sometimes the city is beautiful, sometimes
ugly.

52
00:03:23,910 --> 00:03:28,569
Sometimes Jerusalem is personified as a not
especially reputable mythic woman.

53
00:03:28,569 --> 00:03:34,300
This is particularly true during the Babylonian
captivity, a time in the 6th century BCE when

54
00:03:34,300 --> 00:03:40,170
the babylonian emperor Nebuchadnezzar kept
sacking Jerusalem and sending Jews into exile.

55
00:03:40,170 --> 00:03:44,469
This all led to some complicated feelings
about Jerusalem.

56
00:03:44,469 --> 00:03:46,790
The lamentations of Jeremiah begin:

57
00:03:46,790 --> 00:03:51,980
How doth the city sit solitary, that was full
