did create their own mythological history,

91
00:06:02,050 --> 00:06:03,460
particularly for their city.

92
00:06:03,460 --> 00:06:08,870
We’re going to look at two important myths
surrounding the founding of Rome, involving,

93
00:06:08,870 --> 00:06:13,140
you might be shocked to learn: families and
violence.

94
00:06:13,140 --> 00:06:17,379
One story of the foundation of Rome comes
from Virgil’s epic poem, The Aeneid.

95
00:06:17,379 --> 00:06:22,560
This is the story of the Trojan hero, Aeneas,
who escapes the sack of Troy with his aged

96
00:06:22,560 --> 00:06:27,090
father, his young son, and statues of his
household gods.

97
00:06:27,090 --> 00:06:30,610
Eventually he makes his way to Italy where
he and his group of Trojans settle.

98
00:06:30,610 --> 00:06:35,110
There, Aeneas marries Lavinia, the daughter
of the king of Latium.

99
00:06:35,110 --> 00:06:40,610
Anchises, Aeneas’s dad, dies during the
journey, but in book six of the Aeneid, Aeneas

100
00:06:40,610 --> 00:06:46,550
