156
00:10:19,390 --> 00:10:24,190
These stories, like the ones in the Bible,
remind us how easily myths can gloss over

157
00:10:24,190 --> 00:10:28,580
or sometimes even glamorize terribly violent
actions.

158
00:10:28,580 --> 00:10:33,620
The founding and conquering and defending
of cities can get really ugly.

159
00:10:33,620 --> 00:10:38,350
Some myths reflect this, others choose to
pretty up their origin stories with magic

160
00:10:38,350 --> 00:10:39,350
and stuff.

161
00:10:39,350 --> 00:10:43,760
The story of Rome’s founding highlights
some of the complexity to be found in mythical

162
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:44,760
cities.

163
00:10:44,760 --> 00:10:49,350
Many cities have origin stories, some more
historically grounded than others.

164
00:10:49,350 --> 00:10:53,730
When we’re dealing with actual cities, that
have archaeological and written histories,

165
00:10:53,730 --> 00:10:58,180
we often find that the myths surrounding the
city jibe with that history.

166
00:10:58,180 --> 00:11:02,662
Jericho was besieged and conquered at some
point, though it’s unlikely that trumpet

167
00:11:02,662 --> 00:11:04,280
blasts were responsible.

168
00:11:04,280 --> 00:11:09,220
Rome, built on the Palatine, and became the
seat of one of the most expansive empires

169
00:11:09,220 --> 00:11:10,610
